Let's say you're the boss of a crew of thugs, and you gotta get some cash fast. 
You see a bank with a sweet safe full of cash, and you decide to rob it. 
You and your boys bust in with your masks and guns blazing, and you make off with the cash. 

But then, one of your boys, Buster, gets shot in the leg and can't run as fast as you need him to. 
So you and the rest of the crew have to wait for Buster to catch up.

In programming, this is kinda like a dependency injection. 
You have a service or a class that needs something else to do its job, just like you and Buster needed each other to rob the bank.

Buster is the "dependency," and you are the "injector" who provides him with what he needs.

In C#, you can use a technique called "constructor injection" to pass in the dependency when you create the object.

So, let's say you have a class called BankRobber that needs a buddy to bust in with, you could do it like this:

public class BankRobber
{
  private IHelper helper;

  public BankRobber(Helper helper)
  {
    this.helper = helper;
  }

  public void RobBank()
  {
    this.helper.DoSomething();
  }
}

Then, in your code, you can create an instance of BankRobber like this:

 BankRobber buster = new BankRobber(new Helper());
 buster.RobBank();

 just like how you and Buster teamed up to rob the bank.

 Buster is now the "dependency," and the new Helper() is the "injection" that you're providing him with.

 In C#, all constructors must have an access modifier (public, private, protected). 
 So the BankRobber class can have a public constructor because it needs to be accessible to other classes that may want to create an instance of it.

 The IHelper interface is a marker interface, which means it has no implementations, but it can be used to indicate that an object can provide a particular service. 
 In this case, the BankRobber class is telling the world that it needs an object that can provide a service called "DoSomething."

 The new Helper() call is an example of a "factory method" or a "nop-implementor." 
 It's a way to create an object without actually providing an implementation. 
 In this case, the new Helper() call is a placeholder for a real implementation that will be provided later.

 Whenever you need to rob a bank, you can just create an instance of BankRobber and give it a buddy to bust in with.

 And that's dependency injection in C#! 
 It's a way to decouple objects in your code, so they can work together without being tightly coupled. 
